</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>ACR179:v97#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="ACR179"/><meta name="dc:title" content="ACR &#xA;              179-&#xA;                CHAPTERED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div width="100%" style="text-align:center;"><div id="bill_num_title_chap"><span style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold;font-size:1.1em;font-family:'Times New Roman'; "><b>
                Assembly Concurrent Resolution
              
                        No. 179</b></span></div><div style="text-align:center;padding-top: 1.0em;padding-bottom: 1.2em;" id="chap_num_title_chap"><span style="font-size:1.4em;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-weight:normal;">
                      CHAPTER 113</span></div></div><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> Relative to Wildland-Urban Interface Preparedness and Resilience Day. </span></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center">
                  
                  [<span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Filed with
              </span><span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Secretary of State
              </span> <span style="font-size: 13pt">June 18, 2026.
                      </span>]
                </div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">ACR 179, Flora.
                          Wildland-Urban Interface Preparedness and Resilience Day.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This measure would proclaim May 1, 2026, and the same date annually thereafter, as Wildland-Urban Interface Preparedness and Resilience Day.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_5FAF5E4C-CBA8-4925-885B-16E23E40293B"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, As California continues to rebuild in the wake of devastating wildfires, it has become unmistakably clear that our state’s fire season no longer resembles what it was even at the turn of the century — fire season is now a year-round reality; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_DB666771-1178-44F6-BD3D-C2EB8F72025D"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, California’s Wildland-Urban Interface (WUI) represents an area where homes, communities, and critical infrastructure intermingle with fire-prone wildland vegetation, creating conditions for rapid fire spread, structure-to-structure ignition, and large-loss events across vast areas that are severely at risk for catastrophic wildfire; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_89B531D4-FBF7-4688-B622-F14274AC6E0F"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The scale and consequences of wildfire disasters in California have demonstrated that legacy assumptions regarding fire season, risk, and preparedness are no longer valid, requiring a fundamental shift toward continuous readiness and mitigation; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_63B572CE-0FC4-43C0-AFDD-34F86ABB09DF"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, This year-round threat has placed an increased premium on wildfire resilience measures, including home hardening practices, vegetation management, defensible space maintenance, and community preparedness, all aimed at reducing property loss and preventing civilian and firefighter fatalities; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_142447C0-3C6F-4561-94E3-92254643A0E7"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The frequency, intensity, and duration of wildfires in California have increased significantly in recent decades, placing WUI communities at heightened risk and underscoring the need for year-round preparedness and coordinated resilience strategies; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_CD918715-5598-49BC-AEDB-4908A984B6E6"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, In 2025, the Department of Forestry and Fire Protection responded to over 8,000 wildfires that burned over 525,000 acres, resulting in 31 combined civilian and firefighter fatalities; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_E456D4AD-CF2C-4320-ACE3-D1324998CFB9"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, WUI areas span more than 7,000,000 acres, represent nearly 14,000,000 people — approximately 1 in 3 California residents — and account for the majority of buildings destroyed in California wildfires, making proactive planning, defensible space maintenance, home hardening, and communitywide mitigation efforts essential to protecting lives, property, and natural resources; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_2FD3774F-9DF5-4FED-8098-4E1DEB6A0B33"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, It is appropriate to establish a Wildland-Urban Interface Preparedness and Resilience Day, which will raise public awareness of the unique wildfire risks faced by communities in WUI areas and promote practical actions that reduce the loss of life and property; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_0B2A3817-0282-4406-868B-85B9FBB14F66"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Ensuring fire-resilient communities requires a shared and enforceable commitment among residents, fire agencies, policymakers, and all levels of government to advance coordinated mitigation, planning, and education efforts across the state; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_C54F0B81-DB7D-4215-9E1A-9F75584C7E0A"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Assembly of the State of California, the Senate thereof concurring, That May 1, 2026, and the same date annually thereafter, shall be declared “Wildland-Urban Interface Preparedness and Resilience Day” to mark the start of National Wildfire Awareness Month; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_9DFC0341-21FF-42B1-A9B9-B5D6DB4D7BBF"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That, with the support of the Wildfire Conservancy — a nonprofit organization serving California and the nation in addressing critical issues related to wildfires and the Wildland-Urban Interface — the State of California shall commemorate this day with the goal of fostering a more prepared and resilient California and encourage education, collaboration, and proactive risk-reduction efforts; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_06ECEE88-D90D-4F03-8814-06C98A3758C9"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Chief Clerk of the Assembly transmit copies of this resolution to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
